132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1351
H.P. 874 House of Representatives, April 1, 2025
An Act to Require Antisemitism to Be Considered as Motivation
When Determining a Violation of a Criminal or Civil Law
Received by the Clerk of the House on March 28, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Judiciary pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative GRIFFIN of Levant.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 5 MRSA ยง4553, sub-ยง1-I is enacted to read:
3 1-I. Antisemitism. "Antisemitism" has the same meaning as the nonlegally binding
4 working definition of "antisemitism" adopted by the International Holocaust Remembrance
5 Alliance Plenary in Bucharest, Romania on May 26, 2016.
6 Sec. 2. 5 MRSA ยง4554, sub-ยง5 is enacted to read:
7 5. Antisemitism as motive. When determining whether a violation of this Act or any
8 criminal or civil law has occurred, an assessment of whether antisemitism was a motive, if
9 relevant, for that violation must be made.
10 SUMMARY
1111 This bill defines "antisemitism" as the nonlegally binding working definition of
1122 "antisemitism" adopted by the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance Plenary in
1133 Bucharest, Romania on May 26, 2016. The bill also amends the Maine Human Rights Act
1144 to require that, when determining whether a violation of the Maine Human Rights Act or
1155 any criminal or civil law has occurred, an assessment of whether antisemitism was a
1166 motive, if relevant, for that violation must be made.
